criteria.driver_alignment:
Discover — framed the core tension between EMH and behavioral explanations;  
Implement/Represent — used an event‑study simulation to generate evidence and concretize how information is (not) incorporated;  
Reflect — explicitly synthesizes EMH theory with behavioral explanations (limits to arbitrage, time‑horizon inefficiencies) and derives conceptual conclusions and investment philosophy.

Discover — framed the EMH vs behavioral question and learning goal;  
Represent — explicitly described event‑study design, AR formula and CAPM expected returns;  
Implement/Reflect — applied theory to simulations and the GameStop case and derived practical implications (limits to arbitrage, strategy advice).

Discover — framed the empirical question (efficiency vs behavioral drivers);  
Represent — specified a clear event‑study framework (windows, AR formula, CAPM expected returns) for empirical testing;  
Implement — ran simulations, reported repeated-run outcomes (day‑0 spike + post‑drift) and computed summary metrics (AR, CAR, efficiency ratio);  
Validate/Reflect — discussed statistical and economic significance, robustness concerns, and applied findings to the GameStop case.

Discover — student framed the research question and cited historical numerical claims about GameStop;  
Represent/Implement — built and ran a simulation and described methods;  
Validate — raised questions about statistical/economic significance but did not perform historical data checks.
